{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"03fd2fb4-f1c8-4bf7-8617-405db33ab153","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_014a7arT5uv7gzCnEaLzZkBn","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Applying EF Core 9 fixes"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01JVntRYco95CTqpRNurRSRb","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-5cfbfe90e9dc4992842ec774b833d00d/EfApp.csproj","old_str":"    <TargetFramework>net8.0</TargetFramework>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n  <ItemGroup>\n    <PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.SqlServer\" Version=\"8.0.0\" />\n    <PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.Design\" Version=\"8.0.0\" PrivateAssets=\"all\" />","new_str":"    <TargetFramework>net9.0</TargetFramework>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n  <ItemGroup>\n    <PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.SqlServer\" Version=\"9.0.0\" />\n    <PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.Design\" Version=\"9.0.0\" PrivateAssets=\"all\" />"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"edit the file at /tmp/sv-5cfbfe90e9dc4992842ec774b833d00d/EfApp.csproj."}],"interactionId":"ee592e72-0b00-40c3-84e0-b0f0c4693e03","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now let me analyze all the breaking changes from EF Core 8 to EF Core 9 that apply to this codebase:\n\n1. **Target Framework**: `net8.0` → `net9.0`\n2. **Package versions**: 8.0.0 → 9.0.0\n3. **`HasData` with `DateTime.UtcNow`**: In EF Core 9, `HasData` seed data must use constant values. `DateTime.UtcNow` is evaluated at model-building time which causes issues with migrations - every migration would see a different value. This was already problematic in EF Core 8 but EF Core 9 made breaking changes around seeding. Actually, let me think about this more carefully - `DateTime.UtcNow` in `HasData` has always been a problem but I need to check if EF Core 9 specifically broke this.\n\n\n4. **`Migrate()` inside a user transaction**: EF Core 9 now wraps each migration in its own transaction by default, so calling `Database.Migrate()` within a user-started transaction will throw. I need to either remove the outer transaction or move the migration call outside the transaction scope.\n5. **Cosmos DB breaking changes**: The Cosmos DB provider changed the discriminator property name in EF Core 9, which could affect the separate Cosmos DB project mentioned.\n   - **Discriminator property renamed**: The default changed from `\"Discriminator\"` to `\"$type\"`, so I'll need to configure `HasDiscriminator` to use the old name for backward compatibility with existing documents.\n   - **Synchronous Cosmos DB queries**: EF Core 9 removed support for synchronous queries, so I need to switch to async methods like `.ToListAsync()` and `.FirstAsync()`, or enable `AllowSynchronousIO` on the Cosmos client options if necessary.\n6. **`EnsureCreated`/`EnsureDeleted` now use partition keys** in Cosmos, which could also be a breaking change to watch for.\n\nNow I'll start implementing these fixes. Since the user mentioned a separate Cosmos DB project but I don't see it in the directory, I'll focus on the main project first and address the Cosmos changes if that project becomes visible.\n\nI need to update the `.csproj` file to target `net9.0` and upgrade the EF Core packages, fix the `HasData` configuration to use a fixed date instead of `DateTime.UtcNow`, remove the transaction wrapping in `MigrationRunner`, and provide detailed guidance for the Cosmos DB changes. documentation\n\nActually, for the Cosmos DB part, since the user explicitly asked me to \"identify all breaking changes and provide the exact fixes,\" I should create a file or provide clear code examples. Let me think about what makes sense.\n\nI'll update the existing files and provide clear output about the Cosmos DB fixes.\n\nLet me also verify my knowledge about EF Core 9 breaking changes:\n\n1. **Migrate() in user transaction** - Yes, this is a breaking change in EF Core 9. `Database.Migrate()` now throws if called inside a user transaction because it manages its own transactions internally.\n\n2. **Cosmos discriminator renamed from \"Discriminator\" to \"$type\"** - Yes, this is a breaking change. To preserve compatibility with existing documents, configure: `.HasDiscriminator<string>(\"Discriminator\")`.\n\n3. **Cosmos sync I/O removed** - The Cosmos provider no longer supports synchronous queries, so all queries need to be converted to async.\n\n4. **HasData with DateTime.UtcNow** - This produces a warning because the value changes on every model build, causing spurious migration diffs. EF Core 9 has stricter validation, so I need to use a constant value instead.\n\nNow I'll implement all of these fixes.","outputTokens":1415,"requestId":"2835:2CF44:C8E744:EA3BA6:69EAC6A7"},"id":"9e3ac9b6-a5d8-4892-8c84-b9bf9059bef9","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:26:26.535Z","parentId":"7935bf98-eb67-4d05-b402-d9035a6928c9"}
